I was driving down to my parents house today, in a rather tedious and boring journey, and I started wondering why we can't do this sort of journey to my in-laws house in this length of time. I came up with a solution, that would be faster and easier than anything we currently have. Basically it involves the use of a large tube that would have to be constructed that sits on the bed of the Atlantic, and connects the UK to the USA. This tube would have a mag-lev style train, that runs through it, although it would be similar in functionality to the Eurotunnel, thus you could drive onto it. The tube itself would maintain a tidal powered magnetic field around itself at all times, that encloses a complete vacuum. It would also direct the magnetic field as the method of prepulsion for the train. Since the train would be in a complete vacuum, it would then be able to accelerate indefinately since there would be no frictional forces whatsoever to slow it down. I would imagine the train would then be able to safely accelerate up to about 10,000 mph, up until the mid point when the field reverses and the train starts slowly decelelrating. This would mean that the journey would take about 10 to 20 minutes.

He runs in the room,
He raises his head,
"I'm here!", he says,
"I'm here!", he says.

He jumps on the table,
He jumps on the bed,
"Wake up!", he says,
"Wake up!", he says.

He jumps on the table,
He jumps on my head,
"Feed me!", he says,
"Feed me!", he says.

He bites my fingers,
He bites on my toes,
"I'm hungry!", he says,
"I'm hungry!", he says.

He hears an noise,
and off he goes.
"What was that?", he says,
"What was that?", he says.

He runs in the room,
He jumps on the bed,
"But I'm hungry", he says,
"I'm hungry", he says.

He looks at me puzzled,
as I awake,
"Meow", he says,
"Meow", he says.
Crickey! That Stingray is a big nipper.

I'm wondering how long it'll take me to set up my own asterisk server. I mean, it took me about 6 hours to install a graphics card the other day, and took me about 8 hours to get devhook working on my PSP, and maybe 4 hours to set up postfix. Postfix I really didn't have an excuse for, but at least with devhook I have an exuse that the howtos are in Engrish and the software is somewhat illegal. The graphics card was because the drivers just didn't work, no matter what configuration I used... I was surprised to find proprietry 64 bit linux drivers for a 6 year old pci graphics card on the manufacturers web site. At least the postfix tutorial was a little outdated and my domain settings were wrong, and my firewall was set wrong.

After the recent incidents at Tesco, namely making we wait 30 minutes for a non existent flatscreen TV, along with charging me for some phantom grapes and taking 20 minutes to figure out how to refund me, I was ready to give up on Tesco. Especially since I went to ASDA and was suitably impressed with their prices. However, that all changed when I went back to Tesco again, after all it's closer, and I found that they'd installed self service checkouts. The ones with the touchscreens that tell you what to do. Apart from the obvious geek nature of them, it just shows how competent these cashiers really are. And while a lot of people might have a problem with the dehumanising nature of the ability to go to Tesco, buy a weekly shop, fill up your car, and not communicate with a human being in any way shape or form, I find it quite refreshing. After all, in many ways I'm effecively interacting with what I consider to be my peers. I find it more dehumanising to have to employ people to be slaves to machines, when you might as well interact with the machine directly and more effectively. Someone or some people have spent many hours developing an interface that can be used be a member of the general public. That requires a shit load of work in hci, software development and testing. I suspect a lot of people don't really appreciate how difficult that is.

I've finally gotten comfortably into the trousers I wore last March. They were very tight on me then. I was an XXXXXL then, and moved up to XXXXXXXL by the end of June this year. But then, after some words of advice, I realised I was making excuses not to lose weight. My final goal is simple, although probably quite impossible. I'm worried that I will be denied treatment when I do need it because of the prejudices that the NHS (and Bupa) has towards people, While I can see no reason why I can't, with proper commitment, achieve a weight bracket that they cannot possibly prejudice. Then all I need to do is work on my ethnicity, gender, accent, and age, and then I might receive health care, if I have the right postcode. I think my initial target will be to be able to purchase a cheap suit from Tesco that fits me comfortably. Alas I am a few months off that, but I should be able to before it gets cold again. 

There are a few other advatages of being on the Atkins diet. I have a lot more energy. I wouldn't have been able to overhaul the computer room and install the, hopefully one day complete X10 home automation system, without being on this diet. If I had more money I'd probably be motivated to do the kitchen and garden fences too.

It's amazing how bombarded you are with processed shit all the time. It's everywhere, at work people are handing out junk, they eat junk, they sell junk, all the supermarkets, the TV, it even comes in the mail. I have to take my own lunch to work because everything they sell in the canteen is packed full of carbs and sugar. There are maybe two isles I bother going down in the supermarket, because everything else is just processed.

Still this is the only diet that's ever worked for me.
I don't know why I'm so miserable, I think it might be because it's winter outside and it's supposed to be summer outside. But then, I hate it when it's too hot too.

I'm still relucatant to run XP on any of my PCs at home, not because it's MIcrosoft, but because it's 5 years old. I'd be happy to run Vista if it was out of beta.

I'm also not looking forward to the fact that Big Brother will be over in 5 days. It may be absolute nonsense, but it's certainly entertaining.

So I'm just sitting their quietly minding my own business when this Easter egg hits me at high velocity. I see the perpetrator of this heinous crime was none other than my wife. So I immediately call the FBI in an attempt to procure a charge of spousal battery, but it turns out they're too busy fighting Al Keyda, whoever he is. The next thing I know the whole family is at it. Attempting to subdue me with turkey, ham, and another assortment of creamy vegetable dishes. And then comes the final straw. The attempt to keep me quiet by using beer, of all things. Scared beer, used as a weapon. How dare she? I think it's time she pulled her socks up and smelled the Easter bunny, 'cos I sure as hell wouldn't drink a few pints and fall asleep after a large Easter dinner.

I'm alone again. In many ways I'm used to it. The solitude. I wonder how I can bear to live on my own when I am alone at first. But then I wonder how I can bear to live with other people when I initially do too. It's not so much the way I necessarily feel about a person, but the constant presence, even if it is relatively subconscious, that there is someone else in the same dwelling. It's something you get used to being with, or being without, but either way it takes time to adjust. And yes, I can simulate it with these entertainment machines, the sense of passive conversation from the television, the reassurance of a few letters on a screen, that you instinctively know means that the other person at least has the coherence to leave their connection to a virtual world open. Yet, with solitude, I get used to filling these voids with junk television, and junk food. It feels too normal somehow. I hear the clock ticking, it becomes meaningless. Life becomes meaningless. I see these artificial friends, I see the horrors of the films, of the news, and it all becomes a blur of irrelevance. There's this dull pain where panic and loneliness and anxiety used to be. Apathy. That's how people deal with it.

It's thanksgiving and I'm going to celebrate it for the first time in two years. 3700 miles later, and 465 days apart, it's great being with my wife again, However, I'm just finding it difficult to adjust to the life of effective bachelorism with a 3 bedroom house to myself, a car, and complete control over my finances. I'd forgotten how submissive I have to be, which in itself does have it's own sense of irony, but I do feel completely useless here. Yet, they all, for the most part, despite their relative increments in maturity, some even psychological, all seem to treat me with the same level of respect they did before. I'm not quite sure it is purely because of the mutual fellowship either. It is something else. There is something almost genetic built into this culture that has an unexplainable respect for my sovereign nation.

I also find my list of cultural and technological grievances has grown considerably since I was here last too, although admittedly some are due to the sub-class demographic this household resides in. Things like:

RG58 (yeah really) v.s. UTP Gigabit and Memo Wifi
Composite video RCA v.s. RGB scart
analogue low resolution NTSC v.s. digital higher resolution PAL
110V @ 60Hz v.s. 240V @ 50Hz
GSM v.s. UMTS
Progressive modern rock v.s. DnB

I can't say I care much about the lack of real bread or lack of Marmite or curry, but the toilets are still designed wrong.

I was listening to the radio this morning on the way to work and they had this entire news article on how this orchestra got it's first female conductor. As if women's lib was something new. I find it annoying that we still have to be constantly told about how much we should strive for equality and then make a big deal when these equality standards are met to some degree. I really don't see it as ever having been the case in my lifetime, given the majority of powerful positions I've seen occupied by women. They are somehow glorifying the norm, which is really pointless. Yet, there will still be PC glorification in 10 years time too, blacks, gays, and eventually the obese. But how about this for an idea? Forget about all this political correctness bullshit, and just stop prejudging everyone?

Today has not been a good day. First my car won't start so I'm an hour late for work. Then when I get to work everything goes wrong and I spend all day fixing the shit that I thought I'd fixed last week. Then I come home to find that my most expensive ebay auction has been arbitrarily removed becuase it violates ebay policy... despite there being a good 20 other auctions like it. Then I get a cramp in my leg for 20 minutes when I go to bed that just wouldn't go away. At least it's only a few days to go.

This is a bit better. I've put the original sharp rom back on my zaurus. OZ was buggy, and pdaxrom had no software. While I'm loathed to use such an old kernel. It's a lot better than the alternatives at the moment. Still I got apache with php and openssh working straight away. Now all I need to do is get MySQL running and then qpegps and bluetooth. Since I'm no longer concerned with mp3 or divx support thanks to my Sony(and Alba) hardware. Still it might be nice to have a few games on it.

I feel absolutely awful. I'm at work, for the 13th day in a row. I've got another 6 days before my next day off. I watched about 50 minutes of this Final Fantasy movie earlier. It looked good. It sounded good, despite the Japanese. Yet, I had no idea what was going on or why. Even with the dialogue subtitled I had no idea what was going on. And the dialogue seemed to have no relation at all with the movie, that seemed to go from slow moving family scenes to extreme violence at a whim. Ah, the joy of Japanese film. In any case the headache didn't help. I don't think it's going to go away.

I think there is something wrong with me. I have no imagination. I was thinking the other day what I'd do if money was no object. My mind brings back ideas of buying a *brand new* budget car. A *brand new* entry level computer. Installing an MFI fitted kitchen and bathroom, and going somewhere fancy for dinner... like... the drive through at Burger King...

I dunno, it's scary to think that now I'm starting to pay back this mortgage sized student loan, that is still my idea of luxury.
